  "prompt": "What is the best WYSIWYG editor for Drupal 7?",
  "response": "As of my last update in October 2023, **CKEditor** is widely regarded as the best WYSIWYG (What You See\nIs What You Get) editor for Drupal 7. It is the default editor for Drupal 8 and 9, but it is also fully supported in\nDrupal 7 through the **CKEditor module**.\n\n### Why Choose CKEditor for Drupal 7?\n1. **Ease of Use**: CKEditor offers a clean and intuitive interface that is user-friendly for both content editors and developers.\n2. **Customizability**: You can customize the toolbar, add plugins, and configure the editor to meet specific needs.\n3. **Wide Adoption**: CKEditor is used across many platforms and is well-maintained, ensuring compatibility and support.\n4. **Integration**: It integrates seamlessly with Drupal 7, allowing for easy installation and configuration.\n5. **Accessibility**: CKEditor is designed with accessibility in mind, making it a good choice for modern web standards.\n\n### Key Features of CKEditor:\n- Drag-and-drop file uploads.\n- Image and media embedding.\n- Advanced text formatting options.\n- Support for tables, lists, and other HTML elements.\n- Plugin system to extend functionality.\n\n### How to Install CKEditor in Drupal 7:\n1. **Download the CKEditor module** from the [Drupal.org project page](https://www.drupal.org/project/ckeditor).\n2. **Download the CKEditor library** from [CKEditor.com](https://ckeditor.com/download) and place it in the libraries folder (e.g., `sites/all/libraries/ckeditor`).\n3. **Enable the CKEditor module** in Drupal.\n4. **Configure the CKEditor profile** at `Administration > Configuration > Content Authoring > Text formats and editors`.\n\n---\n\n### Alternatives to CKEditor\nWhile CKEditor is the most popular choice, other WYSIWYG editors for Drupal 7 include:\n\n1. **TinyMCE**: Another widely used editor with similar features to CKEditor. It\u2019s available as a Drupal module and is a good alternative.\n2. **Aloha Editor**: A lightweight and modern editor, though it\u2019s less commonly used than CKEditor or TinyMCE.\n3. **Froala Editor**: A premium editor with a sleek interface and advanced features, but it requires a paid license.\n\nFor most Drupal 7 users, CKEditor remains the best-balanced option in terms of features, ease of use, and compatibility.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
